274
00:10:14,483 --> 00:10:15,745
Did I forget to put it
in my calendar?

275
00:10:15,789 --> 00:10:19,009
- No, no,
we didn't have plans.

276
00:10:19,053 --> 00:10:20,010
I have some news.

277
00:10:20,054 --> 00:10:21,011
- News?

278
00:10:21,055 --> 00:10:22,404
Come, sit, sit.

279
00:10:22,447 --> 00:10:24,493
What is your news?

280
00:10:24,536 --> 00:10:26,626
- Um...my band...

281
00:10:26,669 --> 00:10:29,629
we, uh, kind of have
this cool thing going.

282
00:10:29,672 --> 00:10:31,369
- What cool thing?

283
00:10:31,413 --> 00:10:33,720
- It's a tour, a big tour.

284
00:10:33,763 --> 00:10:35,199
Huge, actually.

285
00:10:35,243 --> 00:10:37,027
We're gonna be on the road
for months.

286
00:10:37,071 --> 00:10:38,115
Now,
I know you don't approve--

287
00:10:38,159 --> 00:10:39,116
- No, no, no, no.

288
00:10:39,160 --> 00:10:41,553
You're following your dreams.

289
00:10:41,597 --> 00:10:43,773
I'm very proud of you, Beta.

290
00:10:43,817 --> 00:10:45,557
I would like to help.

291
00:10:45,601 --> 00:10:47,734
Can I send you some money
while you're on the road?

292
00:10:47,777 --> 00:10:49,692
Isn't that what you call it?
On the road?

293
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:50,780
- Yeah.

294
00:10:50,824 --> 00:10:53,696
But no,
I need to do this on my own.

295
00:10:53,740 --> 00:10:56,438
There's one thing
you could do for me.

296
00:10:56,481 --> 00:10:58,222
- Anything you need.

297
00:10:58,266 --> 00:11:01,399
- Look out for Ella for me.

298
00:11:01,443 --> 00:11:03,358
I don't want her
to feel too alone.

299
00:11:03,401 --> 00:11:05,708
- Oh, of course I will.

300
00:11:15,892 --> 00:11:19,330
- You guys are so annoying--
seriously!

301
00:11:19,374 --> 00:11:21,724
- No, guys, we have to start
over--he didn't say anything.

302
00:11:21,768 --> 00:11:22,812
- It doesn't matter!
- Yes it does.

303
00:11:22,856 --> 00:11:24,814
that's the point of the game.

304
00:11:24,858 --> 00:11:26,642
Say something!

305
00:11:27,643 --> 00:11:29,210
- Okay.
- It's always the same thing

306
00:11:29,253 --> 00:11:31,603
with her--it's like she's
the only one with problems.

307
00:11:31,647 --> 00:11:32,735
- Okay, okay, Shoshanna.

308
00:11:32,779 --> 00:11:34,345
It's fine to have
emotions in here.

309
00:11:34,389 --> 00:11:35,869
Obviously, that's
the whole point,

310
00:11:35,912 --> 00:11:39,307
but let's try to remember
intent versus impact, okay?

311
00:11:39,350 --> 00:11:41,744
Emily, what's going on?

312
00:11:41,788 --> 00:11:42,832
What's happening with you?

313
00:11:42,876 --> 00:11:44,791
- I just feel alone.

314
00:11:44,834 --> 00:11:46,227
- Why do you think
you feel alone?

315
00:11:46,270 --> 00:11:48,272
Come on,
back in the circle here.

316
00:11:48,316 --> 00:11:50,840
- Nobody cares
what I think.

317
00:11:50,884 --> 00:11:52,537
I don't matter
to anyone.

318
00:11:52,581 --> 00:11:53,756
- #truth.

319
00:11:53,800 --> 00:11:55,540
Shoshanna, please.

320
00:11:55,584 --> 00:11:57,847
You know,
it's okay to feel alone.

321
00:11:57,891 --> 00:11:59,457
We all feel alone
from time to time, right?

322
00:11:59,501 --> 00:12:00,720
Even when we aren't, right?

323
00:12:00,763 --> 00:12:02,634
Daniel, what about you?
How do you feel?

324
00:12:02,678 --> 00:12:05,550
- Yeah, I guess
I feel alone sometimes.

325
00:12:05,594 --> 00:12:07,291
And I...

326
00:12:07,335 --> 00:12:08,379
and I just...

327
00:12:09,467 --> 00:12:10,642
- Ooh, hold on.
Emily?

328
00:12:10,686 --> 00:12:11,643
You okay?

329
00:12:11,687 --> 00:12:14,211
- Something...

330
00:12:14,255 --> 00:12:16,213
something smells weird
in here.

331
00:12:17,388 --> 00:12:19,869
Like rotten eggs.

332
00:12:19,913 --> 00:12:22,916
- Okay, well, I'm--
I don't smell anything, so--

333
00:12:22,959 --> 00:12:24,308
- I smell it, too.

334
00:12:24,352 --> 00:12:26,658
Like,
really gross rotten eggs.

335
00:12:26,702 --> 00:12:28,312
- Um, you're all smelling it?

336
00:12:28,356 --> 00:12:30,314
Okay, uh, let's be safe.

337
00:12:30,358 --> 00:12:31,576
Everyone, come on,
let's get up.

338
00:12:31,620 --> 00:12:32,621
Up and out of the class.

339
00:12:32,664 --> 00:12:35,493
We will go
to a less stinky locale.

340
00:12:35,537 --> 00:12:37,147
Come on, Emily, you'll be okay.
Come on.

341
00:12:38,670 --> 00:12:41,238
All right, everybody down.
Yep, you know where to go.

342
00:12:41,282 --> 00:12:42,239
- Something wrong?

343
00:12:42,283 --> 00:12:43,719
- Um, maybe, yeah.

344
00:12:43,763 --> 00:12:46,548
Can you get maintenance?
We may have a gas leak.

345
00:12:49,986 --> 00:12:51,771
- Great news
for Renée Hamrick.

346
00:12:51,814 --> 00:12:53,642
- Oh, the board approved
visiting nurses?

347
00:12:53,685 --> 00:12:54,948
- Not yet,
not by a long shot.

348
00:12:54,991 --> 00:12:56,732
But, once they approve
my new candidate,

349
00:12:56,776 --> 00:12:57,733
I am confident they will.

350
00:12:57,777 --> 00:12:59,169
- That's fantastic.

351
00:12:59,213 --> 00:13:01,389
Who'd you, uh, sucker into
signing up for that?

352
00:13:03,870 --> 00:13:05,697
No, no.

353
00:13:05,741 --> 00:13:07,351
- Yeah.

354
00:13:08,396 --> 00:13:09,484
Just hear me out,

355
00:13:09,527 --> 00:13:10,702
because I need
an ally on the board,

356
00:13:10,746 --> 00:13:12,269
one of us, someone who can
make sure that

357
00:13:12,313 --> 00:13:14,576
when programs like the Visiting
Nurse's Agency come up,

358
00:13:14,619 --> 00:13:16,708
Brantley can't just--
brush 'em aside.

359
00:13:16,752 --> 00:13:19,233
- What time are the meetings?
- 10:30 on Wednesday.

360
00:13:19,276 --> 00:13:21,539
- Look, Max, I'd love to help,

361
00:13:21,583 --> 00:13:23,672
but the reason that the board
meets at 10:30 every Wednesday

362
00:13:23,715 --> 00:13:25,326
is because
they don't have other jobs.

363
00:13:25,369 --> 00:13:26,544
I have surgery.

364
00:13:26,588 --> 00:13:27,850
- It would suck
to miss surgery,

365
00:13:27,894 --> 00:13:30,374
but, it could mean that
the next Renée Hamrick

366
00:13:30,418 --> 00:13:32,855
wouldn't need
additional surgery at all.

367
00:13:32,899 --> 00:13:34,726
So, think about it.

368
00:13:34,770 --> 00:13:36,206
Come on buddy,
what do you say?

369
00:13:36,250 --> 00:13:38,861
Me and you,
shaking things up.

370
00:13:41,777 --> 00:13:42,734
- All right, I'm in.

371
00:13:42,778 --> 00:13:44,519
- Yes, yes!
Thank you.

372
00:13:45,868 --> 00:13:47,304
- Dr. Reynolds?
- Mm-hmm.

373
00:13:47,348 --> 00:13:48,479
- No.
- No?

374
00:13:48,523 --> 00:13:49,698
- $4.75.
- Keep it.

375
00:13:49,741 --> 00:13:51,395
- Oh, thank you.
- No, don't thank her.

376
00:13:51,439 --> 00:13:52,570
she's undermining elections.

377
00:13:52,614 --> 00:13:53,876
- No one's undermining
anything, Max.

378
00:13:53,920 --> 00:13:54,964
- Mm-hmm.

379
00:13:55,008 --> 00:13:56,226
- I'm giving you reality,

380
00:13:56,270 --> 00:13:58,402
a thankless task
which appears to be my lot.

381
00:13:58,446 --> 00:14:00,448
- Dr. Reynolds is accomplished.

382
00:14:00,491 --> 00:14:03,538
He is dynamic, he knows
this hospital inside and out.

383
00:14:03,581 --> 00:14:05,322
- Can Dr. Reynolds raise
seven figures?

384
00:14:05,366 --> 00:14:06,367
No.

385
00:14:06,410 --> 00:14:07,759
Can he donate it himself?
No.

386
00:14:07,803 --> 00:14:08,848
Ergo, he's out.

387
00:14:08,891 --> 00:14:10,327
Money is how programs

388
00:14:10,371 --> 00:14:12,982
like the Visiting Nurse's
Program gets funded.

389
00:14:13,026 --> 00:14:14,679
If you want to play this game,

390
00:14:14,723 --> 00:14:17,334
bring me a candidate
the board can actually use.

391
00:14:17,378 --> 00:14:18,727
- Like another rich sycophant?

392
00:14:18,770 --> 00:14:21,556
- Like a CEO, a hedge fund
manager, or a celebrity.

393
00:14:21,599 --> 00:14:23,601
Better yet, all three.

394
00:14:23,645 --> 00:14:24,602
Happy hunting!

395
00:14:27,954 --> 00:14:30,782
Oh, oh.

396
00:14:30,826 --> 00:14:33,437
- Okay, um...

397
00:14:33,481 --> 00:14:34,612
- Is Emily gonna be okay?

398
00:14:34,656 --> 00:14:36,527
- I'm handling it, Daniel.

399
00:14:36,571 --> 00:14:38,007
- You didn't exactly
answer the question.

400
00:14:38,051 --> 00:14:39,530
- Okay, you know what?
That's enough.

401
00:14:39,574 --> 00:14:40,749
Head to the classroom,
everybody.

402
00:14:40,792 --> 00:14:42,577
Thank you, I'll be there
in a second.

403
00:14:42,620 --> 00:14:43,621
Thank you.

404
00:14:43,665 --> 00:14:45,406
Here, yeah, come on.
Take a seat.

405
00:14:48,017 --> 00:14:50,280
Not feeling any better, huh?

406
00:14:50,324 --> 00:14:53,283
- My head still hurts
and I'm seeing spots.

407
00:14:53,327 --> 00:14:54,850
- Yeah, you know, natural gas,

408
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:56,634
it can deprive
our body of oxygen

409
00:14:56,678 --> 00:14:58,810
and it causes all these
nasty little symptoms.

410
00:14:58,854 --> 00:15:00,334
It's called hypoxia.

411
00:15:00,725 --> 00:15:02,466
- No gas leak.

412
00:15:02,510 --> 00:15:03,772
- I'm sorry, what?

413
00:15:03,815 --> 00:15:05,469
No gas leak?
Um, hang on.

414
00:15:05,513 --> 00:15:06,949
Just keep breathing,
okay kiddo?

415
00:15:06,993 --> 00:15:08,559
What are you talking about?

416
00:15:08,603 --> 00:15:10,431
Emily is literally retching
her guts up on the floor.

417
00:15:10,474 --> 00:15:13,086
- Building services checked
the entire floor twice.

418
00:15:18,439 --> 00:15:20,832
- All right, page Kapoor.

419
00:15:20,876 --> 00:15:22,704
Thank you.

420
00:15:22,747 --> 00:15:24,706
- I don't want any trouble.

421
00:15:24,749 --> 00:15:26,316
- I understand that,
Mr. Martinelli,

422
00:15:26,360 --> 00:15:27,796
but we need you to tell us

423
00:15:27,839 --> 00:15:29,493
what you've seen
at your construction site.

424
00:15:29,537 --> 00:15:31,756
- Any old signs of labels
talking about cobalt,

425
00:15:31,800 --> 00:15:32,975
or other heavy metals?

426
00:15:33,019 --> 00:15:34,324
- No, nothing like that.

427
00:15:34,368 --> 00:15:35,760
- What about old insulation?

428
00:15:35,804 --> 00:15:37,371
- They're running
a clean shop, I swear,

429
00:15:37,414 --> 00:15:38,720
and they're square by me,

430
00:15:38,763 --> 00:15:40,591
especially how they treated me
since my accident.

431
00:15:40,635 --> 00:15:41,766
- What accident?

432
00:15:41,810 --> 00:15:43,855
- I was welding early on
on the joists,

433
00:15:43,899 --> 00:15:45,988
fell 10 feet
and shattered my hip.

434
00:15:46,032 --> 00:15:47,816
- Gosh, you're lucky
that was all.

435
00:15:47,859 --> 00:15:49,861
- And I was out a while.

436
00:15:49,905 --> 00:15:52,690
But the foreman,
after my hip replacement,

437
00:15:52,734 --> 00:15:53,865
put me on site hauling.

438
00:15:55,389 --> 00:15:56,738
He didn't have to do that.

439
00:15:56,781 --> 00:16:00,002
- Um, what do they have
you doing as a site hauler?

440
00:16:00,046 --> 00:16:01,569
- Driving the trash away.

441
00:16:01,612 --> 00:16:03,963
It's the cushiest job
I've ever had for the money.

442
00:16:04,006 --> 00:16:06,835
- Mr. Martinelli, are you okay
if we check something?

443
00:16:08,402 --> 00:16:09,359
- With that?

444
00:16:09,403 --> 00:16:10,404
- All you're gonna feel

445
00:16:10,447 --> 00:16:12,623
is a slight pinch
and some pressure.

446
00:16:28,030 --> 00:16:32,034
- Bloom, that's not blood.

447
00:16:37,953 --> 00:16:39,172
- What the hell?

448
00:16:39,215 --> 00:16:40,521
- Mr. Martinelli,

449
00:16:40,564 --> 00:16:43,611
you're being poisoned
by your artificial hip.

450
00:16:43,654 --> 00:16:45,961
- Emily's symptoms could be
caused by any number of things.

451
00:16:46,005 --> 00:16:47,615
I need to order
some further tests.

452
00:16:47,658 --> 00:16:48,920
- Oh, come on,
don't give me that.

453
00:16:48,964 --> 00:16:50,748
Your beautiful mind
already has a diagnosis.

454
00:16:50,792 --> 00:16:51,923
No.

455
00:16:51,967 --> 00:16:54,013
I have a hypothesis.

456
00:16:54,056 --> 00:16:57,451
I suspect Emily is suffering
from a complex migraine.

457
00:16:57,494 --> 00:16:59,105
- A complex migraine?
- Iggy!

458
00:16:59,148 --> 00:17:00,976
Come quick,
something's wrong.

459
00:17:01,020 --> 00:17:01,977
- What?

460
00:17:05,589 --> 00:17:07,200
- Oh, whoa.

461
00:17:09,854 --> 00:17:12,031
You might need to revise
that hypothesis.

462
00:17:14,642 --> 00:17:16,296
- So, Renée Hamrick is here

463
00:17:16,339 --> 00:17:17,514
for an I&D
in the primary closure

464
00:17:17,558 --> 00:17:19,299
